SIMPLE: gloom
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gloom
<hw>Gloom</hw> <pr>(gl⟦oomac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>gl⟦omac⟧m</ets> twilight, from the root of E. <ets>glow</ets>. See
<er>Glow</er>, and cf. <er>Glum</er>, <er>Gloam</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Partial or total darkness; thick shade; obscurity;
<as>as, the <ex>gloom</ex> of a forest, or of midnight</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A shady, gloomy, or dark place or grove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before a <qex>gloom</qex> of stubborn-shafted oaks.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson .</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Cloudiness or heaviness of mind; melancholy; aspect
of sorrow; low spirits; dullness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sullen <qex>gloom</qex> and furious disorder prevailed by
fits.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In gunpowder manufacture, the drying oven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Darkness; dimness; obscurity; heaviness;
dullness; depression; melancholy; dejection; sadness. See
<er>Darkness</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gloom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gloom
<hw>Gloom</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gloomed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Glooming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shine or appear
obscurely or imperfectly; to glimmer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become dark or dim; to be or appear dismal,
gloomy, or sad; to come to the evening twilight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The black gibbet <qex>glooms</qex> beside the way.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[This weary day] . . . at last I see it <qex>gloom</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gloom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gloom
<hw>Gloom</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To render gloomy or
dark; to obscure; to darken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A bow window . . . <qex>gloomed</qex> with limes.</q>
<rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A black yew <qex>gloomed</qex> the stagnant air.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill with gloom; to make sad, dismal, or
sullen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a mood as that which lately <qex>gloomed</qex>⟦br⟧
Your fancy.</q> <rj><qau>Tennison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What sorrows <qex>gloomed</qex> that parting day.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>gloomful</ent>⟦br⟧
